items.title: Hands on: Lenovo Yoga Chromebook C630 review
items.description:
akramkennis posted a photo:



By Chris Willis / Sep 12, 2018 9:44 AM

The Lenovo Yoga Chromebook C630 has been launched at IFA 2018, boasting a large, 15.6-inch 4K display, a screen that folds into a tablet and a top notch metal body.

This is a premium Chromebook, and one that's probably not going to be given to an excessive number of undergrads. Rather, the Yoga Chromebook is aimed more at business professionals looking for a laptop with better than average battery life for emails, web perusing, content editing, presentations and the occasional piece of video streaming.

Lenovo Yoga Chromebook release date and price

The Lenovo Yoga Chromebook release date is set for the finish of October in Europe, the Middle East and Africa. We're yet to hear what availability will be in the US and Australia.

The Lenovo Yoga Chromebook price starts at ‚Ç¨799 (around $940, ¬£720, AU$), which will get you the full HD display and a lesser chipset in the engine - and it's not clear yet what the top end price will be for the 4K screen and most powerful i5 processor.

Design and display

The full metal design of the Lenovo Yoga Chromebook offers up a top notch look and feel, enhancing its appeal to the professional, business market.

As the Yoga part of the name proposes, this Chromebook features Lenovo's 360 degree folding screen, allowing you to push the screen all the way onto the back of the laptop - turning it into a tablet.

You can also have it standing up in tent mode, keyboard down and screen up in introducing mode and the more traditional laptop mode with the keyboard in front of the screen.

The pivots feel strong and capable of taking regular changes in modes as the screen is rotated around.

Thanks to its large screen, the Yoga Chromebook is somewhat of a beast - although relatively thing - at 361.5 (14.23") x 248.85 (9.8") x 17.8mm (0.7").

It's not something you'll want to carry around with you daily either, with that full-metal body bringing about a starting weight of 1.9kg.

Lifting the Yoga Chromebook up its weight was immediately noticeable, especially compared to the budget Chromebooks which offer basically the same experience (albeit on smaller, bring down resolution displays, in plastic frames with less power in the engine).

The full QWERTY keyboard is a decent size, and the keys are illuminated to aid composing in darker situations. We found the keys somewhat flat though, with a low amount of travel which doesn't profit extensive stretches of composing.

Meanwhile, there's a large trackpad beneath, giving you plenty of space to parchment, drag and drop - but with the Yoga Chromebook also boasting a touchscreen you may not have to use the trackpad all that much.

The headline spec is the Lenovo Yoga Chromebook's 4K (3840 x 2160) IPS touchscreen, and it looks fantastic. Bright and colorful, it's ideal for a 4K Netflix gorge.

It's by all account not the only display alternative on offer here though. If you fancy saving yourself a tad of cash, the Yoga Chromebook will also be available with a full HD (1920 x 1080) IPS touchscreen.

Specs and features

In the engine of the Lenovo Yoga Chromebook you're looking at up to eigth-gen Intel Core i5 Kaby Lake R Processors, 8GB of DDR4 RAM, the decision of either 64GB or 128GB of storage, stereo speakers, 720p HD webcam and up to 10 long periods of battery life.

It means the lightweight Chrome OS ticks along pleasantly, opening Chrome and the various apps rapidly with not clear stammers amid our brief timeframe with the laptop.

The Lenovo Yoga Chromebook also boasts a pleasing array of ports, including two USB-C ports, one USB-A port, a microSD opening and a 3.5mm headphone jack.

As for wireless availability, there's Intel WiFi 8265 2x2 802.11 ac and Bluetooth 4.1 StonePeak on-board the Yoga Chromebook.

Early verdict

The Lenovo Yoga Chromebook is an attractive, premium laptop with potentially solid battery and beautiful 4K display.

However, Chromebooks are as yet restricted by Chrome OS and the apps available on it, which means any heavy lift tasks -, for example, video altering - are somewhat more difficult to achieve, and when you consider the price of the Yoga Chromebook it's harder to justify.

That said, if you're in the market for a premium Chromebook with a respectable amount of power and a great display this could be the one for you.
